[2026-04-30] fix: 5.1.4 — web-dom panic on truncated/missing close tags
  source: real bug report from main2's state-statute scraper grind —
  `codemap web-dom` panicked on legislature.maine.gov index with
  "byte index 17379 is out of bounds of `<!doctype html ...`" at
  codemap-core/src/actions/reverse/web.rs:891:34. The 17378-byte HTML
  is truncated mid-document (no closing </button>). Pre-fix
  extract_buttons fell back to `unwrap_or(content.len())` when the
  closing tag was missing, then `pos = close + 1` made the next
  iteration's `lower[pos..]` slice OOB.

  Same antipattern lived in extract_forms, extract_tables (outer +
  inner <th>), extract_navs, and extract_buttons — five sites total.
  Fix in all five: replace the `unwrap_or(content.len())` fallback
  with `let Some(...) = ... else { break };` — a missing close tag
  means the document is truncated, which is end-of-scan, not a body
  that extends to EOF. Loops also gained a `pos < lower.len()` guard
  before slicing.

  Defense in depth: also swept `actions/reverse/{web,schema,pe}.rs`
  to convert all 58 `to_lowercase()` calls to `to_ascii_lowercase()`.
  HTML/URL/header data is ASCII, and `to_ascii_lowercase()` preserves
  byte length — so even existing index-into-other-string usages stay
  sound under Unicode input. Smaller, faster, and immune to a class
  of latent bugs from the same shape.

  New regression test test_web_dom_handles_truncated_tags_without_panic
  materializes four truncated HTML fragments (open <button>/<form>/
  <table>/<nav> with no closes) and asserts web-dom returns Ok rather
  than panicking. 54 tests passing (was 53).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.2.0 — heterogeneous graph + 5 new graph algorithms
  source: Charles asked "did we add the graphs to the reverse engineering
  thing" — exposing that every RE action's signature was `_graph: &Graph`
  (underscore = unused), meaning PE imports / web-blueprint API maps /
  schema tables / etc. produced text reports but never participated in the
  graph that pagerank/hubs/bridges operated on. Charles followed up with
  "is there better ways to graph more up to date stuff" + "search arxiv" —
  led to the right architecture by reviewing GitHub stack-graphs,
  petgraph, NetworkX, and Joern source.

  Architecture (informed by stack-graphs Node enum + Joern pass-based CPG):
    - EntityKind enum on every GraphNode — 20 variants spanning source
      files, PE/ELF/Mach-O/Java/WASM binaries, DLLs, symbols, HTTP
      endpoints, web forms, schema tables/fields, proto messages,
      GraphQL types, OpenAPI paths, Docker services, Terraform resources,
      ML model files, .NET assemblies/types.
    - Each RE action signature flipped from `_graph: &Graph -> String`
      to `graph: &mut Graph -> String`; each is now a Joern-style "pass"
      that mutates the shared graph by registering kind-tagged nodes
      and edges.
    - Cache version 8 → 9 (existing source-file nodes default-tag,
      backwards compat via serde defaults).
    - Graph helpers added: ensure_typed_node, add_edge, nodes_by_kind,
      meta_path.

  Pass coverage (every RE action now registers typed nodes):
    pe-imports/exports → PeBinary + Dll + Symbol with edges
    pe-strings/resources/debug/sections → PeBinary
    dotnet-meta → PeBinary + DotnetAssembly
    elf/macho/java/wasm → respective binary kinds
    clarion-schema → SchemaTable + SchemaField with field edges
    sql-extract → SchemaTable per detected table + join edges
    dbf-schema → SchemaTable for the file
    web-api / web-blueprint / js-api-extract → HttpEndpoint per call,
      with edges from source files (cross-domain "meta-path source->endpoint")
    web-dom → WebForm per form action
    web-sitemap → page nodes + internal-link edges
    proto/openapi/graphql/docker/terraform → kind-tagged schema source
    gguf/safetensors/onnx/pyc/cuda → MlModel with format attrs

  New algorithms (cribbed from NetworkX catalog — they ship 17, we add 4):
    betweenness — Brandes' O(VE) chokepoint algorithm. Continuous score
      complementing the binary `bridges` action.
    eigenvector — power-iteration centrality. PageRank without damping.
    katz — eigenvector + attenuation factor (α=0.1, β=1.0 default).
    closeness — 1 / Σ shortest-path distance.

  Heterogeneous-only:
    meta-path <kindA>-><kindB>[->kindC] — DFS through typed edges
      following a kind sequence. The killer feature for cross-domain
      analysis. Defaults capped at 200 paths.
    `--type kind1,kind2` filter on every centrality measure (target
      doubles as the kind list).

  Visualization:
    dot — kind-aware shapes/colors. SourceFile=box (default), PeBinary=
      component+blue, ElfBinary=component+green, Dll=folder, Symbol=oval,
      HttpEndpoint=oval+green, WebForm=parallelogram, SchemaTable=cylinder,
      SchemaField=note, ProtoMessage=tab, DockerService=box3d,
      TerraformResource=box3d+purple, MlModel=note+orange.
    mermaid — classDef declarations matching the dot palette.

  Tests: 64 passing (was 54). 10 new heterogeneous-graph tests including
  meta-path traversal, betweenness chokepoint detection, type filter
  isolation, idempotency of ensure_typed_node + add_edge, EntityKind
  round-trip parsing.

  Intentionally deferred to 5.2.x / 5.3:
    - Leiden community detection (wiki strongly endorses; current `clusters`
      uses LPA which is functional but inferior). Faithful Leiden impl
      with refinement step is 500-800 LOC of careful code; queued.
    - Per-resource node registration for OpenAPI paths, Proto messages,
      GraphQL types, Docker services, Terraform resources (currently they
      register only the schema source). Each adds 30-100 LOC to the
      respective parse function.
    - Trait-based graph algorithm interface (petgraph pattern) so
      algorithms work over arbitrary graph structures, not concrete
      Graph type. Bigger refactor; not in 5.2.0 scope.
    - Group / load / harmonic / percolation / current-flow centrality
      measures (NetworkX has these; we shipped the 4 most useful).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.3.0 — Leiden clustering + 3 more centrality + per-resource schemas
  source: 5.2.0 explicitly deferred Leiden community detection, per-resource
  schema-node registration, and additional centrality measures from the
  NetworkX catalog. 5.3.0 closes those out.

  Leiden community detection (actions/leiden.rs, ~330 LOC):
    Faithful implementation of Traag, Waltman, van Eck 2019
    "From Louvain to Leiden: guaranteeing well-connected communities"
    (arXiv 1810.08473). Three phases: local moving (greedy modularity
    gain), refinement (the Leiden secret sauce — within each Louvain
    community, reset nodes to singletons and merge only when the
    well-connectedness criterion is satisfied), aggregation. Iterates
    until convergence.

    `clusters` action default switched from LPA → Leiden. LPA still
    available via `clusters lpa`. Two-clique synthetic test confirms
    Leiden recovers the expected partition.

  Centrality additions (actions/centrality.rs):
    - harmonic   — Marchiori & Latora 2000. Σ 1/d. Handles disconnected
                   graphs natively (unlike closeness).
    - load       — Newman 2001. Variant of betweenness, useful as
                   sanity check on graphs with parallel shortest paths.
    - structural-holes — Burt 1992. Effective size + constraint.
                   Identifies brokers between otherwise-disconnected
                   groups. Aliased as `brokers`. In codebases this maps
                   to integration files (frontend↔backend, business-
                   logic↔persistence) — exactly the high blast-radius
                   spots refactors should know about.

    Centrality measure count: 4 → 7. Still 10 short of NetworkX's 17,
    but the most-cited & most-useful are all in.

  Per-resource schema node registration (actions/schemas.rs):
    Closes the 5.2.0 deferral. Each schema action now produces typed
    nodes for individual resources, not just the schema source:
      - openapi-schema → OpenApiPath + HttpEndpoint per path operation,
        with operation_id attrs. Spec paths and runtime endpoints share
        a node, so meta-paths against either kind work.
      - proto-schema   → ProtoMessage per message + intra-file field-type
        composition edges (msg → msg when field type matches another
        message in the same file).
      - graphql-schema → GraphqlType per type + `implements` edges.
      - docker-map     → DockerService per service + depends_on edges.
        `pagerank --type docker` now finds the most-depended-on services.
      - terraform-map  → TerraformResource per block + reference edges
        (approximate via attribute-value tokenization — proper HCL
        parsing deferred).

  Tests: 72 passing (was 64 in 5.2.0). 8 new tests covering Leiden
  recovery on a two-clique graph, default-algorithm dispatch, LPA
  fallback, unknown-algo error path, harmonic + load + structural-
  holes invocation, and the brokers alias.

  Action count: 101 → 104 (+ harmonic, load, structural-holes).

[2026-04-30] fix: 5.3.1 — typed-node cache persistence + RE-action ID alignment
  source: real-world validation of 5.3.0 surfaced two issues:
    1. RE-action mutations (HttpEndpoint/SchemaTable/etc nodes) lived
       only inside a single CLI invocation and got thrown away on
       process exit. Two-step workflows like
         `codemap js-api-extract src/ && codemap meta-path source->endpoint`
       returned 0 paths because the second invocation started fresh.
    2. ID-scheme mismatch: web-action `register_endpoint` anchored
       endpoints to `file:<source>` while the scanner produced bare
       relative paths like `src/client.js`. Source→endpoint edges
       therefore connected disjoint id namespaces.

  Fixes:
    - scanner.rs: cache version 9 → 10. CacheData now carries a
      `typed_nodes` Vec alongside `files`. save_cache writes both;
      load_cache hydrates non-source nodes back into the graph.
    - actions/mod.rs: dispatch wraps the inner match in a fn that runs
      `scanner::persist_typed_nodes(graph)` after every action. RE
      actions now flush their mutations every invocation.
    - actions/reverse/web.rs: new `source_node_id` resolver — checks
      direct match → strip-prefix match → suffix match → fallback. RE
      actions anchor to the scanner's actual node id when one exists,
      so meta-paths stitch correctly.

  Validation: created src/client.js with two fetch calls; ran
  `js-api-extract src/` in process 1, then `meta-path source->endpoint`
  in process 2. Result: 2 paths found (one per fetch). pagerank --type
  endpoint also surfaces them.

  New regression test test_typed_node_cache_persists_across_invocations
  drops the post-extract Graph (simulating process exit) and re-scans
  to verify the meta-path output reads cached endpoints. 73 tests
  passing (was 72).

