  to silence the Node 20 deprecation warnings GitHub Actions emits on
  every run.

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.5.0 — 4 more centrality measures (7 → 11 of 17 from NetworkX)
  source: NetworkX ships 17 centrality measures, codemap had 7. Closing
  the gap with the next 4 most useful:

    voterank — Zhang et al. 2016. Iterative voting elects k spreaders;
      each round elects the highest-vote node and decays its neighbors'
      voting capacity. Output is the spreaders in selection order.
      In codebases: "which files would have outsized impact if changed".
    group — degree centrality of an arbitrary node SET (not single node).
      Target syntax `codemap group table` treats every SchemaTable as
      the group; reports group reachability + cohesion. Useful for
      whole-cluster refactor impact analysis.
    percolation — Piraveenan et al. 2013. Like betweenness but each
      path s→t weighted by source's "percolation state" (we use degree
      as proxy since codebases lack inherent state).
    current-flow — Newman 2005. Random-walk variant of betweenness
      (BFS approximation, not full Laplacian inverse — exact is
      O(VE × N²) per pair).

  Aliases: brokers → structural-holes, current-flow-betweenness →
  current-flow.

  Tests: 80 passing (was 75). +5 new tests.

  Action count: 104 → 108 (+ voterank, group, percolation, current-flow).
  Centrality coverage 7 → 11 of 17 NetworkX measures. Still ~6 short
  (subgraph_alg, second_order, dispersion, reaching, trophic, voterank's
  k-influencer set variant) — those are more situational.

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.5.1 — `pipeline` composite action chains RE+analysis steps
  source: cache-persistence (5.3.1) made multi-process composition work,
  but for one-shot scripted workflows `pipeline` is cleaner — single CLI
  invocation, deterministic, no .codemap/ state dependency.

  Syntax:
    codemap pipeline "action1:target1,action2:target2,...,final:target"

  Each comma-separated entry is `action:target` (or just `action` for
  no-target actions like pagerank). Steps run in order against the
  same Graph; final step's output is what gets printed. Errors halt
  the pipeline; preceding mutations remain in the graph and persist
  to cache.

  Examples:
    codemap pipeline "js-api-extract:src/,meta-path:source->endpoint"
    codemap pipeline "pe-imports:foo.exe,pe-exports:foo.exe,pagerank:"
    codemap pipeline "clarion-schema:db.clw,sql-extract:app.exe,meta-path:source->table"

  Implementation: composite::pipeline parses the target string, calls
  dispatch_inner (now pub(crate)) per step, collects step summaries +
  final output. Errors abort with the full step log so users see where
  things broke.

  Tests: 83 passing (was 80). +3 new tests covering chain success, help
  text, error halting.

  Action count: 108 → 109 (+ pipeline).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.6.0 — auto-classify binary/ML/schema files during scan
  source: heterogeneous graph foundations were complete in 5.2.0+, but
  using them required either explicit RE actions (pe-imports, gguf-info,
  proto-schema) or `pipeline`/cache-persistence to compose. Plain
  `codemap structure` only saw source files because scanner walked
  SUPPORTED_EXTS only.

  scanner::auto_classify_typed_files: post-walk pass that walks the scan
  tree for binary / ML / schema extensions and registers typed nodes
  without deep content parse. Light-weight — just file-level metadata
  (path, size, category) — but enough to make graph queries see them.

  Extensions auto-classified:
    Binaries: .exe .dll .sys → PeBinary
              .so → ElfBinary
              .dylib → MachoBinary
              .class .jar → JavaClass
              .wasm → WasmModule
    ML:       .gguf .safetensors .onnx .pyc .fatbin .cubin → MlModel
    Schema:   .proto → ProtoMessage source
              .tf → TerraformResource source
              .clw .txa .txd → SchemaTable (Clarion)
              .dbf → SchemaTable (dBASE)

  ID-prefix matches what explicit RE actions register (pe:, elf:, model:,
  schema:proto:, etc.) so a later `codemap pe-imports foo.exe` augments
  the existing node rather than creating a duplicate.

  Each auto-classified node carries `auto_classified: true` attr so RE
  actions can detect "I'm enriching a stub" vs "I'm creating fresh".

  Result: `codemap pagerank --type pe` works on a binary directory after
  `codemap structure` alone. No RE action needed for first-pass triage.

  Tests: 84 passing (was 83). +1 new test materializes 7 file types and
  verifies all 6 EntityKind variants are detected.

