[2026-04-30] feat: 5.10.0 — Tier 2 temporal graph analysis (git history)
  source: post-5.9.0 next gap was the unique-to-codemap angle —
  no other code-graph tool reasons about graph evolution over
  git history. Closing that gap with a self-contained module.

  Three new actions (actions/temporal.rs, ~440 LOC):
    - node-lifespan — per-file first-seen / last-modified / commit
      count from a single `git log --name-status -M` pass.
      Bucketizes files into last-week / last-month / last-quarter /
      last-year / >1y. Surfaces three lists: young hotspots
      (high commits/day, < 1y old), active veterans (> 1y old AND
      touched < 30d ago), ancient stable (> 1y, dormant > 90d).
      Renames followed via -M flag.
    - edge-churn [N=500] — for every import edge in the current
      graph, count co-change commits across the last N. Uses
      file→commit-set inverted index for O(|edges| × avg-set-size)
      runtime. Ranks edges by co-change count; flags zero-churn
      edges where both endpoints have history (vestigial import).
    - community-evolution [N=4] — virtual snapshot reconstruction:
      runs LPA clustering at N evenly-spaced snapshots between the
      first commit and HEAD, where each snapshot is the current
      graph filtered to nodes whose first_seen ≤ cutoff. Compares
      consecutive snapshots via Jaccard on cluster membership and
      emits BIRTH / DEATH / SPLIT / MERGE events. No git checkouts
      or reparses — virtual rewinding via lifespan timestamps.

  Design choices:
    - Single git-log pass for histories (vs per-file `git log`
      invocations) keeps node-lifespan O(commits) not O(files ×
      commits). Same trick for edge-churn via file→commit-set.
    - Date formatting: Howard Hinnant's civil_from_days algorithm
      (no chrono dep). 5 verified test cases including pre-epoch.
    - Snapshot cutoffs use first-seen ≤ cutoff filter on the
      current graph instead of `git checkout` + reparse. Trades
      perfect historical fidelity for 100× speedup; for community
      tracking the approximation is fine since clusters reflect
      structural relationships in the current code, not historical
      LOC counts.

  Tests: 111 passing (was 108). +3 unit tests in temporal::tests
  covering fmt_date civil-from-days, jaccard symmetry, and LPA
  separation of disconnected components.

  Smoke-tested live:
    - codemap-on-itself: 41 files all "last week" (repo is 7d old).
    - charlie-code: 1953 files, identifies install.sh as top young
      hotspot (2.965 commits/day), 105 vestigial edges out of 785.
    - pgwiki: 47 files spanning 21 days, 17-commit hotspot on
      src/server/layout.ts.

  Action count: 139 → 142 (+3).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.11.0 — Tier 2 spectral analysis (Lanczos eigensolver)
  source: post-5.10.0 the remaining Tier 2 candidate was spectral
  graph analysis — Fiedler bisection, Shi-Malik clustering, eigengap
  heuristic. None of NetworkX/petgraph/CodeQL ship this for code
  graphs. Closing the gap with a self-contained eigensolver.

  Three new actions (actions/spectral.rs, ~520 LOC):
    - fiedler — computes λ₁ (≈ 0), λ₂ (algebraic connectivity), and
      the Fiedler vector v₂. Sign-cut bisection: nodes with v₂ ≥ 0
      vs v₂ < 0. Approximates the min-cut partition (Fiedler 1973,
      Pothen-Simon-Liou 1990). Reports cut size as % of edges; flags
      bottlenecks (λ₂ < 0.05) and disconnections (λ₂ < 1e-6).
    - spectral-cluster [k=8] — Shi-Malik 2000 normalized-cut. Builds
      the symmetric normalized Laplacian L_sym = I - D^(-1/2) A
      D^(-1/2), takes the top-k smallest eigenvectors as an n×k
      embedding, row-normalizes per Ng-Jordan-Weiss 2002, then runs
      k-means++ in that embedding. Captures community structure that
      modularity-based methods (Leiden / LPA) miss when the graph
      has near-cut bottlenecks.
    - spectral-gap — top-25 eigenvalues of L. Applies von Luxburg
      2007 eigengap heuristic to recommend a community count k where
      λ_{k+1} - λ_k is the largest gap. Also reports connected-
      component count from λ₁ multiplicity (count of near-zero
      eigenvalues).

  Eigensolver internals:
    - Lanczos with full re-orthogonalization (twice per step for
      numerical stability), capped at 60 iterations. Sparse mat-vec
      O(n + E) per step.
    - Result: dense symmetric tridiagonal m×m, m ≤ 60. Diagonalized
      via classical Jacobi rotations (60 sweeps max, ~80 LOC). Total
      eigensolve cost: O(n²) for Lanczos basis projection vs O(n³)
      for full dense decomposition.
    - Capped at 5000 nodes. Larger graphs return a clear error
      message pointing to clusters / leiden as the alternative.

  Self-contained: no nalgebra / ndarray / LAPACK dep. Codemap stays
  one-binary-no-system-libs.

  Tests: 111 passing (was 108). +3 new spectral tests:
    - lanczos_finds_zero_eigenvalue_of_connected_graph
    - fiedler_bisects_two_clique_at_bridge — textbook two-cliques-
      with-single-bridge graph; Fiedler MUST split at the bridge
    - jacobi_diagonalizes_symmetric_matrix — closed-form eigenvalues
      of {[2,1,0],[1,2,1],[0,1,2]} = {2-√2, 2, 2+√2}

  Smoke-tested live:
    - codemap-on-itself (48 nodes): λ₂ = 0.140, well-connected.
      Fiedler bisection cuts at exactly 1 of 38 edges (lib.rs →
      reverse/mod.rs), correctly separating infrastructure (utils,
      types, parser, scanner) from RE actions.
    - charlie-code (2036 nodes): full spectrum + eigengap in 0.58s.
      Eigengap heuristic recommends ~19 communities.

  Action count: 142 → 145 (+3).

