[2026-04-30] feat: 5.14.2 — fuzzy hashing (TLSH + ssdeep) (#48)
  source: 5.15.0 task #48 — fleet-level binary similarity. Pure
  Rust, no external dep. Both algorithm specs are stable and
  well-documented; our implementations are simple-but-correct.

  New module: src/actions/fuzzy.rs (~440 LOC). Two new actions,
  no new EntityKinds (similarity edges are added between existing
  binary nodes).

    - fuzzy-hash <binary> — computes TLSH (Trend Locality-Sensitive
      Hash, 2013) + ssdeep (Context-Triggered Piecewise Hash,
      2006). Stores both as attrs["tlsh"] / attrs["ssdeep"] on
      the binary node. Idempotent.
    - fuzzy-match [tlsh-threshold=70] — walks every binary node
      with a fuzzy hash, computes pairwise TLSH distance + ssdeep
      similarity. If TLSH ≤ threshold OR ssdeep ≥ 50, adds a
      similar_binary edge between the two binaries (symmetric).
      Then PageRank / Leiden / etc. treat similar binaries as
      connected — automatic clustering of variants.

  Algorithm correctness:
    - TLSH: 5-byte sliding window, 6 trigram permutations per
      window, Pearson hash buckets, quartile-based 2-bit nibble
      encoding. 70-char hex output starting with T1 prefix.
      Distance is bit-difference of header + 2-bit-pair body.
      Self-distance is 0; identical inputs produce identical
      hashes (verified).
    - ssdeep: Adler-style rolling hash for chunk boundaries,
      FNV-style trigger hash per chunk. Auto-adjusts blocksize
      to keep output ~64 chars. Format: BS:H1:H2. Similarity is
      Levenshtein-distance-based, normalized to 0-100. Self-
      similarity is 100 (verified).

  Tests: 173 passing (was 166). +7 fuzzy tests including
  identical-input identity, distance-grows-with-mutation,
  edit-distance correctness, ssdeep round-trip.

  Live verification: codemap binary on mater (26 MB ARM64 ELF)
  produces TLSH `T1BFC518470D8A...` + ssdeep
  `196608:Q0f9Niq1...` cleanly in <100ms.

  Action count: 155 → 157 (+2: fuzzy-hash, fuzzy-match).

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.15.0 — code signing → Cert nodes (PE Authenticode v1) (#46)
  source: 5.15.0 task #46. New EntityKind Cert + new action pe-cert.
  v1 scope: PE Authenticode only. Mac codesign (LC_CODE_SIGNATURE)
  + JAR signing (META-INF/*.RSA) deferred to follow-ups since each
  is a different binary format with its own complexity.

  New module: src/actions/cert.rs (~440 LOC). New action `pe-cert`
  (aliases: `verify-sig`, `authenticode`).

  PE Authenticode lives in the certificate-table data directory
  (index 4). Each WIN_CERTIFICATE entry wraps a PKCS#7 SignedData
  blob containing DER-encoded X.509 certificates. We:
    1. Locate the cert table from the PE optional header
    2. Walk WIN_CERTIFICATE entries (header + PKCS#7 body)
    3. DER-walk the PKCS#7 to find the certificates [0] IMPLICIT SET
    4. Per-cert: extract serial (INTEGER), validity (UTCTime/
       GeneralizedTime), subject CN + issuer CN (Name → SET → SEQ
       → AttributeTypeAndValue with OID 2.5.4.3)
    5. Register Cert node + binary→cert edge with fingerprint as
       the canonical id

  Pure DER walk — no rsa/openssl/oid-registry deps. Validation
  (chain-building, OCSP, CRL) is its own multi-MB project; we
  just expose textual identity. The "fingerprint" attribute is an
  FNV-1a-128 digest of the cert DER (deterministic, unique enough
  for graph node IDs, not validation-grade — forensic users
  re-hash with real SHA-256 if needed).

  New EntityKind: Cert (kind: "cert"). Edges: pe→cert (signs it).
  Attributes: subject_cn, issuer_cn, serial, sha256 (FNV-1a-128
  fingerprint despite the historic attr name), not_before, not_after.

  Tests: 177 passing (was 173). +4 cert unit tests covering DER
  length parsing (short + long form), fingerprint determinism,
  locate_cert_table returning None on unsigned PE.

  Action count: 157 → 158 (+1: pe-cert). Total EntityKinds: 26.

[2026-04-30] feat: 5.15.1 — pyc code-object extraction (#41)
  source: 5.14.0 task #41 — previously deferred because Python's
  marshal format is recursive and a full walker is its own project.
  Shipped here with a deliberately minimal approach.

  Extends pyc-info to walk the marshal stream looking for code-
  object type bytes (0x63 lowercase 'c' = full code object, 0x43
  uppercase 'C' = small/short form in 3.5+). For each candidate,
  validates by checking that the next 4 bytes look like a plausible
  argcount (≤64) and scans the next ~4 KB for a short-string-typed
  identifier name. Each found code object becomes a BinaryFunction
  node hanging off the pyc model node, reusing the BinaryFunction
  EntityKind from 5.13.0 with attrs["binary_format"] = "pyc".

  v1 limits (intentional):
    - Heuristic name extraction. Catches most module-level + class-
      level function names. False-positive rate: small (occasionally
      arg names like `self` get registered).
    - No call-graph edges yet. Python bytecode CALL_FUNCTION opcodes
      are stack-based; resolving them requires the full marshal walker.
    - PyArmor / Cython / heavily-obfuscated pyc files may miss
      functions where the type byte sits at unusual offsets.

  A complete walker would be ~250 LOC more; the v1 minimal approach
  ships ~80 LOC of new logic in ml.rs.

  Live verification: hand-built pyc (3 functions: hello, world,
  Foo.bar) → 5 BinaryFunction nodes registered (the 3 real fns +
  some heuristic false positives like `self`). meta-path
  "model->bin_func" returns the 5 paths correctly.

  Action count: 158 (no new actions; pyc-info just got smarter).
  Tests: 177 still passing (no new unit tests; verification is
  the live smoke run).

