[2026-04-30] feat: 5.18.0 — LSP actions write to the graph (#52)
  source: post-5.17.0 audit identified that all 5 lsp_* actions
  in actions/lsp.rs took &Graph (immutable, ignored) and emitted
  text-only output. LSP returns the richest semantic data in the
  toolkit — symbols / references / call hierarchy / diagnostics /
  types — and none of it landed in the heterogeneous graph. This
  release closes that gap with bounded promotions per action.

  Bounds (per single action invocation):
    MAX_LSP_SYMBOLS_PER_CALL = 5000
    MAX_LSP_REFS_PER_CALL    = 1000
    MAX_LSP_CALL_EDGES       =  500

  These caps prevent LSP responses on large repos (tens of
  thousands of symbols, millions of references on common APIs)
  from blowing up the graph. The cap is reported in the action s
  text output so users know when truncation occurred.

  Promotions added:

  1. lsp_symbols → Symbol nodes (recursive walker).
     Each promotable DocumentSymbol kind (Class / Method /
     Property / Field / Constructor / Enum / Interface /
     Function / Variable / Constant / EnumMember / Struct)
     becomes a Symbol node with attrs name, source=lsp,
     lsp_kind (string), lsp_kind_code (numeric), file, line.
     Edge: source_file → symbol. Non-promotable kinds (Module,
     Namespace, Object literals, Property/Key noise) are
     skipped, but the walker recurses into their children so
     legitimate methods nested under noise wrappers still land.
     Recursion depth capped at 8.

  2. lsp_references → usage edges.
     The query targets one symbol at file:line:col. v1
     registers that target as a single Symbol node
     (lsp_kind=ReferenceTarget) once, then for each reference
     location, adds a referrer_file → target_symbol edge. This
     answers "which files reference X" via outgoing-edge
     traversal of the symbol node — concretely usable via
     `pagerank --type symbol` to find the most-referenced
     LSP symbols across a codebase.

  3. lsp_calls → call edges.
     Registers the prepareCallHierarchy target as a Symbol
     (lsp_kind=CallTarget). For each incoming call, registers
     the caller as a Symbol (lsp_kind=CallParticipant) and
     adds a caller→target edge. For each outgoing call, same
     pattern but target→callee. Source-file edges land for
     all participating symbols.

  4. lsp_diagnostics → SourceFile attrs.
     No new nodes — counts attached to each existing/created
     SourceFile node: lsp_errors, lsp_warnings, lsp_info,
     plus lsp_first_error (truncated to 200 chars) for quick
     triage. Enables `pagerank --type source` ranking by
     error density.

  5. lsp_types → SourceFile attrs.
     lsp_typed_symbols + lsp_total_symbols counts surface
     type-coverage gaps without storing huge hover bodies.
     Files with many untyped symbols rank low.

  Implementation: src/actions/lsp.rs ~250 LOC of additions.
  All 5 action signatures flipped from &Graph to &mut Graph;
  no call-site changes needed (mod.rs auto-coerced &mut Graph
  to &Graph for the immutable signatures). New helpers:
    lsp_kind_is_promotable(i64) -> bool
    register_lsp_symbols(&mut Graph, file_id, symbols, written, depth)
    register_call_edge(&mut Graph, call, key, target, caller_to_target)
    file_id_for_graph(&Graph, &Path) -> String

  Tests: 191 passing (was 189). +2 new lsp_symbol_walker unit
  tests covering (a) promotable-kind filtering — Object kind
  is skipped while its child Method is recursed into and
  registered, (b) cap enforcement — walker stops exactly at
  MAX_LSP_SYMBOLS_PER_CALL when fed payload of cap+100. Real
  rust-analyzer round-trip not added because it would slow CI
  by 10-15 seconds; unit tests cover the walker contract.

  Action count: 163 (unchanged — all 5 LSP actions already
  existed). EntityKinds: 29 (unchanged; LSP symbols reuse the
  existing Symbol kind via attrs).


[2026-04-30] feat: 5.19.0 — close more graph-integration gaps (#53)
  source: post-5.18.0 audit identified more actions parsing
  structured findings without writing to the heterogeneous
  graph. This release closes gaps G2/G3/G7/G8 + adds the
  Dependency EntityKind.

  Promotions added:

  G7: dep_tree → Dependency nodes + dead_deps marking.
     - New EntityKind Dependency (29 → 30). Each declared dep
       promotes to dep:{ecosystem}:{name} node, namespaced by
       package ecosystem (cargo / npm / pypi / go / composer /
       maven / rubygems) so same-name pkgs across ecosystems
       don t collide. attrs: name, version, group (deps /
       dev-deps / etc.), ecosystem, optionally is_dead.
     - dep_tree + dead_deps signatures flipped to &mut Graph.
     - Both functions now self-discover manifests by walking
       scan_dir directly, since the scanner s SUPPORTED_EXTS
       excludes .toml / .json (avoiding lockfile noise) and
       previously dep_tree found nothing on real codebases.
     - dead_deps marks dead Dependency nodes with is_dead=true
       for cleanup-PR generation via attribute filter.
     - Killer queries: meta-path "source->dependency" for
       inventory, pagerank --type dependency for most-used deps
       in a monorepo, attribute-filter is_dead=true for cleanup.

  G7: api_surface → HttpEndpoint nodes for routes.
     - signature flipped to &mut Graph. Each discovered HTTP
       route (Flask @app.route / FastAPI @router.get / Express
       app.get) promotes to ep:{path} HttpEndpoint with
       discovered_via=api_surface attr + edge from source file.
       Joins the same graph surface as openapi-schema /
       web-blueprint / robots-parse for uniform meta-path
       "source->endpoint" queries across discovery modes.

  G3: pe_debug → Symbol node for PDB path.
     - PDB filename + CodeView GUID + age now promote to a
       Symbol node (kind_detail=pdb_path) hanging off the PE
       binary. Implementation lifts the values from the parsed
       text output via stable-format prefix matching ("  PDB: "
       / "  GUID: " / "  Age: ") to avoid duplicating the PE
       walk. Useful for matching a stripped binary to its
       symbol-server PDB without re-running pe_debug.

  G8: ELF/Mach-O entry points → BinaryFunction nodes.
     - parse_elf_with_deps now also returns e_entry; elf_info
       promotes it to bin_func:elf:{target}::entry with
       binary_format=elf, kind_detail=entry_point.
     - New extract_macho_entry walks LC_MAIN (cmd=0x80000028);
       macho_info promotes entryoff to bin_func:macho:{target}
       ::entry. Returns None for older binaries using
       LC_UNIXTHREAD (rare on modern macOS). Handles fat
       binaries by recursing into first arch.
     - pe_meta s entry_rva (was attrs-only) also promotes to
       a BinaryFunction node now, parity across formats. All
       three populate the same kind_detail=entry_point shape
       so cross-binary attribute queries work uniformly.

  G2: pe_resources → VS_VERSION_INFO attrs on PeBinary.
     - Same stable-prefix-lift technique as pe_debug. Lifts
       FileVersion / ProductVersion / CompanyName / FileDescription
       / OriginalFilename / ProductName / LegalCopyright /
       InternalName as vsinfo_* attrs on PeBinary node. Cross-
       binary inventory ("every binary signed by Microsoft" /
       "every NSIS-built installer in this corpus") via
       attribute filter.

  Bridges sweep (gpu_functions, monkey_patches, dispatch_map):
     - read-only over scan-built node.bridges data (already
       populated during scan walk). No gap. Confirmed.

  Tests: 193 passing (was 191). +2 regression tests:
    - test_dep_tree_promotes_to_graph_nodes — Cargo.toml +
      package.json with three Cargo deps (incl. dev-dep) and
      two npm deps; asserts ecosystem-namespaced Dependency
      nodes registered with manifest→dep edges.
    - test_api_surface_promotes_routes_to_endpoints — FastAPI
      sample.py with @router.get + @router.post; asserts
      HttpEndpoint nodes registered with discovered_via=
