[2026-05-01] feat: 5.20.0 — ML model granular nodes (#54)
  source: post-5.19.0 audit identified G6 as the largest
  remaining graph-integration gap — gguf / safetensors / onnx
  parsers extracted full tensor lists + graph operators but only
  registered the parent MlModel as a graph node. The structured
  data died in text output. This release closes G6 by adding
  two new EntityKinds and refactoring all three parsers to
  expose their structured data for promotion.

  New EntityKinds (30 → 32):

  MlTensor — a tensor inside a model file (GGUF / SafeTensors /
    ONNX initializer). attrs: name, dtype (F32 / F16 / Q4_K /
    BF16 / etc.), shape (comma-joined dims), model_format,
    optionally size_bytes / params. Edge: model → tensor.
    Capped at 5000 per model (StringLiteral / LSP-symbol parity).

  MlOperator — operator node in an ONNX graph (Conv / MatMul /
    Add / Relu / etc.). attrs: name, op_type, count_in_model,
    model_format. Aggregated by op_type so a 1000-node ResNet
    surfaces as ~30 unique MlOperator nodes (one per type with
    count attr) instead of 1000 individual nodes — keeps the
    graph tractable on production-sized models. Edge: model →
    operator.

  Refactors:

  parse_gguf — return type from Result<String> to
    Result<(String, Vec<GgufTensorInfo>)>. The local TensorInfo
    struct hoisted to module-scope GgufTensorInfo so the
    promotion helper consumes the same shape. gguf_info now
    calls promote_ml_tensors after parse, registering each tensor
    as an MlTensor node.

  parse_safetensors — same shape change. Local TensorEntry struct
    hoisted to SafetensorsTensorInfo. Includes size_bytes from
    data_offsets diff for cross-tensor inventory queries.

  parse_onnx — return type adds (BTreeMap<String,usize>,
    initializer_count). op_counts + initializer_count hoisted out
    of the if-let-Some(graph_data) block to function scope so
    they re visible at return. onnx_info aggregates op_counts by
    op_type into MlOperator nodes; attaches initializer_count +
    op_type_count as attrs on the parent MlModel for cross-model
    architecture comparison.

  Killer queries unlocked:
    meta-path "model->tensor"           inventory tensor shapes
                                        across a SafeTensors corpus
    pagerank --type ml_operator        find dominant op types
                                        across an ONNX-model corpus
    attribute-filter dtype=Q4_K        find every quantized GGUF
                                        tensor across a fleet
    attribute-filter op_type=LSTM      find every model that
                                        contains LSTM

  Tests: 194 passing (was 193). +1 regression test
  test_safetensors_info_promotes_tensors_to_graph — fabricates a
  minimal valid safetensors file (3 tensors in JSON header), runs
  safetensors-info via execute(), asserts:
    - 3 MlTensor nodes registered with correct names
    - each has model_format / dtype / shape attrs
    - each has an edge from the parent MlModel
    - EntityKind round-trips via from_str / as_str for both
      tensor and ml_operator aliases

  Implementation: src/actions/ml.rs ~120 LOC of additions, plus
  ~10 LOC each of EntityKind plumbing in types.rs / graph_theory.rs /
  exports_format.rs. No new dependencies.

  Action count: 163 (unchanged — promotions added to existing
  actions). EntityKinds: 30 → 32 (+MlTensor, +MlOperator).

  Outstanding gaps after this ship — 2 left, both deferred:
    G4 pe_sections — section table not graph nodes (would need
      new PeSection EntityKind, marginal value alone).
    G5 binary_diff — diff results not graph edges (needs design
      pass: same-graph or cross-graph?).


[2026-05-01] feat: 5.21.0 — BinarySection EntityKind for pe_sections (#55)
  source: post-5.20.0 audit had G4 (PE section table parsed but
  not graph nodes) flagged as deferred — marginal value alone.
  Charles asked to knock it out anyway as polish. This release
  closes G4 with a generic BinarySection EntityKind (designed
  to also cover ELF / Mach-O sections in a follow-up ship
  without needing yet another EntityKind).

  New EntityKind (32 → 33):

  BinarySection — section inside a binary (PE .text / .data /
    .rdata, ELF section header table entry, Mach-O section).
    attrs: name, binary_format (pe/elf/macho), virtual_size,
    raw_size, virtual_address, entropy (Shannon bits/byte),
    characteristics (read/write/exec/code flags joined by +).
    Edge: binary → section. Killer queries:
      attribute-filter entropy>7.0 on --type section
        → packed/encrypted sections across a binary corpus
      meta-path "pe->section"
        → layout enumeration
      pagerank --type section
        → shared section names across vendor product families
      attribute-filter characteristics=*exec*
        → executable sections uniformly across a corpus

  Implementation: extends pe_sections.flag_packed_and_overlay
  (already walking sections to compute max_section_entropy).
  The same loop now also reads section name (8 bytes ASCII,
  null-padded), virtual_size (offset 8), virtual_address
  (offset 12), raw_size (offset 16), characteristics (offset
  36), and registers a BinarySection node per section. New
  helper pe_section_characteristics() decodes the
  Characteristics flag bits into a compact "code+exec+read"
  string so attribute filters work uniformly.

  Tests: 195 passing (was 194). +1 round-trip test confirms
  EntityKind::BinarySection parses through "section" /
  "binsection" / "binarysection" aliases. The section-walking
  code path itself has been in production since 5.12.0 (was
  computing max_section_entropy already); my additions are
  pure ensure_typed_node calls inserted into that loop.

  Action count: 163 (unchanged). EntityKinds: 32 → 33
  (+BinarySection).

  Outstanding gaps after this ship — only 1 left:
    G5 binary_diff — diff results not graph edges. Genuinely
      needs a design pass (same-graph with versioned binary
      nodes, or cross-graph with separate diff edges between
      two scans?). Punted to its own design conversation.


[2026-05-01] feat: 5.22.0 — binary_diff cross-graph promotion (Option B) (#56)
  source: post-5.21.0 audit had G5 (binary_diff signature is
  &mut Graph but ignored) flagged as the LAST remaining graph-
  integration gap, deferred for design input. Charles picked
  Option B (cross-graph): the diff result lives in a separate
  diff: namespace so it never pollutes main-scan nodes.

  Design (Option B cross-graph diff):

  All diff nodes namespaced under diff:{session}: where session
  is a stable FNV-1a 64-bit hash of both file paths. Re-running
  the same diff produces the same node IDs → idempotent (no
  ghost accumulation across runs). Order-sensitive (left vs
  right matters: side a is always the first argument).

  Nodes registered per binary_diff invocation:

  Two PeBinary nodes (pe:diff:{session}:a and :b) with attrs
    name, path, size, diff_session, diff_side, plus diff-summary
    counts (diff_added_funcs / diff_removed_funcs /
    diff_added_dlls / diff_removed_dlls / diff_size_delta).

  One BinaryFunction node per unique imported symbol across
    both sides, with diff_status attr in {added, removed,
    unchanged}. Same node receives edges from BOTH binary nodes
    when status is `unchanged` (so the function appears with
    edges from both pe:diff:{session}:a AND :b). Cap of 5000
    function nodes per call to stay consistent with other ML/
    string caps.

  One Dll node per imported library, same diff_status pattern.
  Coarser-grained companion to the function-level promotion.

  Killer queries unlocked:

    attribute-filter diff_status=added           — new functions
    attribute-filter diff_status=removed         — deleted functions
    attribute-filter diff_session={hash}         — scope to one diff
    pagerank --type bin_func                     — most central across both
    meta-path "pe->bin_func"                     — per-side enumeration
    pagerank --type dll                          — most-imported DLLs across both

  Implementation: src/actions/reverse/pe.rs binary_diff signature
  flipped from _graph: &mut Graph to graph: &mut Graph. Promotion
  block inserted after the existing import-comparison logic
  (collected added/removed/unchanged sets that previously only
  produced text counts). New helper binary_diff_session_id() uses
  FNV-1a 64-bit on path1 + null + path2.

  Tests: 197 passing (was 195, +2). New unit tests in pe.rs:
    - binary_diff_session_id_is_stable_and_order_sensitive
      (idempotency + order-sensitivity + 16-char hex format)
    - binary_diff_handles_missing_file_gracefully (returns
      File-not-found, no graph nodes leaked)

  Action count: 163 (unchanged). EntityKinds: 33 (unchanged —
  reuses existing PeBinary / BinaryFunction / Dll via diff_status
  attr).

  ALL GRAPH-INTEGRATION GAPS NOW CLOSED.

  Session arc 5.16.2 → 5.22.0 (8 releases): closed 8/8 audited
  gaps, added 5 new EntityKinds (Secret + Dependency + MlTensor +
  MlOperator + BinarySection), wired LSP / dep_tree / api_surface /
  pe_debug / pe_meta / pe_resources / elf_info / macho_info /
  cuda_info / pyc_info / gguf_info / safetensors_info / onnx_info /
  pe_sections / binary_diff / secret_scan into the heterogeneous
  graph. Tests 187 → 197 (+10). Action count steady at 163 (every
  win was a quality promotion to existing actions).


[2026-05-01] feat: 5.23.0 — DEX bytecode walker + permission heuristics (#57)
  source: post-5.22.0 review identified mobile (specifically full
  DEX decompilation) as a real weakness. Charles flagged that he
  plans to build mobile apps and would actually use this — so the
  workflow shifted from "malware analysis" to "did I ship a
  permission I am not using / did I forget to declare one I AM
  using?" That made permission→method linking the centerpiece.

  Implementation:

  New module src/actions/dex.rs (~510 LOC):
    - DEX file format header validation (`dex\n035` / `dex\n037`
      etc.) + endian check (0x12345678 little-endian).
    - String / type / method ID table builders. ULEB128 decoder.
    - class_def + class_data walk: for each class, read 4 ULEB128
      sizes (static/instance/direct/virtual fields/methods), then
      walk the encoded_method list with delta-encoded method_idx.
      Emits Vec<DexMethod> with class_name (Java FQN), method_name,
      access_flags, code_off.
    - Per-method bytecode scan for `invoke-*` opcodes (35c form
      0x6E-0x72, 3rc form 0x74-0x78). Pulls method_idx from byte
      offset 2 of each invoke instruction, looks up callee class
      + name, matches against ~30 well-known protected Android APIs
      (Camera / LocationManager / TelephonyManager / SmsManager /
      ContactsContract / BluetoothAdapter / WifiManager / etc.).
      Per-callsite dedup so a method that calls Camera 10 times
      only gets one Permission edge.
    - dex_instruction_width() opcode-width table for resync —
      unknown opcodes default to 2 bytes (one code unit).

  apk.rs integration:
    - try_extract_uncompressed extended to handle compression
      method=8 (deflate) via miniz_oxide. Real APKs always deflate
      classes.dex; v1 (5.15.3) was stored-only and would silently
      skip every real-world APK.
    - apk_info now iterates every classes*.dex entry, calls
      dex::parse_dex on the inflated bytes, registers each method
      as bin_func:dex:{target}::{dex_file}::{i} BinaryFunction
      node with edge from the AndroidPackage. Cap 5000 methods
      per APK. Multidex (classes2.dex, classes3.dex) supported.
    - For each heuristic Permission edge, the Permission node
      auto-registers with discovered_via=dex so the diff between
      manifest-declared permissions and code-referenced ones is
      queryable via attribute filter. This is the workflow Charles
      asked for.

  Killer query unlocked:
    meta-path "permission->method"
      → "what code uses CAMERA permission?"
    attribute-filter discovered_via=dex on --type permission
      → permissions referenced in code but not declared in manifest
    pagerank --type bin_func with binary_format=dex filter
      → most-central methods inside the app

  New dependency: miniz_oxide 0.8 (pure-Rust deflate decoder, MIT/
  Apache, no system libs, used only inside actions/apk.rs).

  Tests: 201 passing (was 197). +4 unit tests in dex.rs:
    - jvm_descriptor_round_trip — Landroid/foo/Bar; → android.foo.Bar
    - uleb128_decodes_canonical_values — wikipedia LEB128 examples
    - api_to_permission_covers_obvious_cases — Camera/Location/
      Telephony API → permission mapping with method-name refinement
    - parse_dex_rejects_non_dex — graceful error on bad magic

  Action count: 163 (unchanged — apk-info gained capability, no
  new action). EntityKinds: 33 (unchanged — DEX methods reuse
  BinaryFunction via binary_format=dex attr).

  Out of scope for v1 (deferred):
    - Full Dalvik opcode catalog (we only decode invoke-* widths
      precisely; other opcodes resync on next valid opcode).
    - PScout-style 100K-row method→permission database (v1 is
      heuristic name-matching against ~30 well-known APIs — gets
      the obvious cases, misses the long tail).
    - Method body call-graph edges (intra-DEX). v1 only emits
      method→permission edges, not method→method. Add later if
      needed.
    - Annotations, parameter type signatures, native method
      signatures.

  This + 5.24.0 (ARM/AArch64 disasm via yaxpeax-arm) = mobile-
  complete codemap: APKs get full graph coverage on both Java
  (DEX) and native (ARM) sides.


[2026-05-01] feat: 5.24.0 — ARM/AArch64 in bin-disasm (mobile day 2) (#58)
  source: post-5.23.0 mobile arc continues. DEX walker (5.23.0)
  covered the Java side of APKs; this release adds the native side
  by extending bin-disasm to ARM and AArch64 ELFs (the .so files
  inside lib/arm64-v8a/ etc.).

  Decision: function-inventory v1, no yaxpeax-arm dep yet.
  - Pulling yaxpeax-arm would add a real disassembler and unlock
    intra-binary call edges + per-function instruction decoding.
  - But: the existing ELF symbol-table walk already gives us the
    function inventory (every STT_FUNC entry with st_size).
  - Charles s actual mobile workflow is "what is in the .so files
    my Flutter / RN app ships?" — function names + sizes get him
    800f the value with zero new deps.
  - If demand emerges for call edges (e.g. tracing a specific
    native function s callers across the binary), a v2 ship adds
    yaxpeax-arm in ~200 LOC.

  Implementation:

  src/disasm.rs:
    - DisasmResult gains `arch: &static str` ("x86"/"x64"/"arm"/
      "aarch64") + #[derive(Debug)] for tests.
    - disasm_elf machine check expanded: 3, 0x3E, 0x28, 0xb7 all
      pass; rejects everything else with a message that lists the
      supported set.
    - Symbol-table walk extended to capture st_size (previously
      discarded). starts vec changed from (String, u64) to
      (String, u64, u64).
    - Branch after symbol walk: x86/x64 use existing decode_functions
      (iced-x86 path); ARM/AArch64 use new functions_from_symbols.
    - functions_from_symbols: for each STT_FUNC inside .text, build
      DisasmFunction with size from st_size (default 4 if zero —
      one ARM/AArch64 instruction), instruction_count = size/4,
      empty calls vec, indirect_calls=0. Sets is_entry when the
      symbol VA matches the ELF entry_va.
    - disasm_pe also fills in `arch` = "x86" or "x64" based on
      bitness so all DisasmResults are arch-tagged uniformly.

  src/actions/bin_disasm.rs:
    - PeBinary/ElfBinary node now gets an `arch` attr.
    - Each BinaryFunction node gets a `binary_format` attr from
      r.arch — uniform with the existing dex/jvm/dotnet/wasm/cuda/
      pyc binary_format scheme.

  Killer queries unlocked for mobile:
    pagerank --type bin_func with binary_format=arm/aarch64 filter
      → most-central native functions in your APK
    meta-path "elf->bin_func"   on a native lib → function inventory
    attribute-filter binary_format=aarch64
      → every AArch64 function across all analyzed binaries (cross-APK
        comparison)

  Tests: 204 passing (was 201, +3 disasm.rs unit tests):
    - functions_from_symbols handles zero-st_size (defaults to 4)
      + filters out-of-text symbols + sets is_entry correctly
      + verifies no call edges produced (would require disasm)
    - disasm_binary rejects unknown ELF machine with helpful
      error message that lists ARM/AArch64
    - DisasmFunction Debug round-trip (smoke for the derive)

  Action count: 163 (unchanged — bin-disasm gained capability).
  EntityKinds: 33 (unchanged).

  Mobile arc complete: 5.23.0 (DEX walker) + 5.24.0 (ARM/AArch64
  disasm) = APKs get full graph coverage on both Java and native
  sides. `apk-info` enumerates DEX methods + permissions; explicit
  `bin-disasm <path/to/lib.so>` enumerates native functions. The
  pieces compose for Charles s "did I ship a permission I am not
  using?" + "what native code is in my app?" workflows.

  Out of scope for v1 (defer until needed):
    - yaxpeax-arm-based real disasm with intra-binary call edges.
    - MIPS / RISC-V / PowerPC / SPARC ELFs.
    - Auto-disasm of every native lib inside an APK during apk-info
      (avoid blowup on multi-ABI APKs; user explicitly invokes
      bin-disasm per .so they care about, or chains via codemap
      pipeline).


[2026-05-01] feat: 5.25.0 — `codemap think` natural-language goal router (#59)
  source: post-5.22.0 second-opinion review identified the #1
  critical gap: with 163 actions, even AI agents hit choice
  paralysis and default to safe-but-wrong picks. The "passive
  recon" workflow specifically suffered because the right path
  (download + web-dom + web-blueprint + js-api-extract) was not
  obviously easier than the wrong path (curl + grep, or worse,
  live scrape). This release ships the orchestrator that fixes
  both problems in one action.

  Design:

  - Goal classifier: case-insensitive substring match against ~18
    intent buckets. Order-sensitive (specific intents first).
    No embedding model, no LLM call inside the binary — just a
    deterministic keyword table. Fast, easy to test, easy to
    extend.

  - Pipeline catalog: each Intent maps to a Vec<PipelineStep> with
    (action, target). Targets are either the user-provided file
    path (for actions like pe-imports) or empty (for graph-walking
    actions like audit/pagerank).

  - Path detection: tokens in the goal that exist on disk become
    the pipeline target. Common surrounding punctuation stripped.

  - Live URL guard: any http:// or https:// token in the goal is
    rejected up-front with "codemap is pure-static; capture the
    artifact first" + a copy-pasteable curl + think invocation.
    Enforces the no-active-network invariant uniformly without
    relying on user/AI memory.

  - Fallback guidance: when no intent matches, list closest intents
    as suggestions instead of guessing.

  Output: header (Intent / Goal / Target / Pipeline) + per-step
  body + footer recap of the pipeline so the user can run the
  same actions directly next time.

  Implementation: src/actions/think.rs (~370 LOC). Calls existing
  super::dispatch() per step — same code path the CLI uses for
  explicit invocations. No special casing, no recursion.

  Promoted to Tier 0 in plugin SKILL.md — the new "I don't know
  what to use" entry point above all 163 specific actions.

  Tests: 209 passing (was 204, +5):
    - classify_goal_covers_common_intents (16 strings)
    - classify_goal_falls_back_when_no_keywords_match
    - detect_path_in_finds_existing_files
    - live_urls_are_rejected_with_passive_only_message
    - empty_goal_returns_usage

  Action count: 163 -> 164 (+think). EntityKinds: 33 (unchanged).

  Closes the highest-leverage usability gap from the post-arc
  audit. Both Mobile and Think (the two review-flagged criticals)
  are now shipped. What's left is housekeeping — examples/
  directory + CONTRIBUTING.md, plus deferred ARM-call-edges via
  yaxpeax-arm if demand emerges.


